  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "tVhxUGcxJzxjyIB3PYO37d9yfrY=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:36.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Decision\n\nLive collaboration on a document exposes **no per-editor cursors, no collaborative selection highlights, and no per-field presence**. The only live surface is the document toolbar's existing **History view**, where peer ops appear in real time, attributed to the correct signer.\n\n## Rationale\n\n- Powerhouse editors are too varied \u2014 tables, visual canvases, dashboards, button grids, forms \u2014 for a single cursor/selection abstraction to be meaningful across all of them.\n- Building per-editor collaborative cursor support would require each editor to opt in with custom instrumentation, a large ongoing maintenance cost.\n- The History view is already part of every document editor, already renders op-by-op, and already attributes ops to signers. Adding a real-time feed into it is the minimal integration.\n\n## UX implication\n\nCollaboration feels like 'watching the history tick in real time' rather than 'watching someone type in the same document'. That's a deliberate tradeoff \u2014 the reactor's op-attributed model is richer than a cursor ever could be, just presented differently.\n\n## What still needs design\n\n- A **Collaborate tab** in the chat panel: pick drive/doc, multi-select participants, send invite \u2192 arrives as a chat card with `[Join]` / `[Decline]`.\n- Drive-level ACT first, doc-level narrowing later.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:36.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:36.000Z"
    }
  },
